<TITLE> Kenya's inflation seen falling to 12-15 pct: minister </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NAIROBI, April 21 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Kenya's year-on-year inflation could fall to about 12-15 percent in coming months, from 21.8 percent in March, as refugees from post-election violence return to farms and food output increases, a minister said on Monday. "(Bank lending) rates have sort of stabilised at between 12 and 15 percent. We would expect also the inflation to be around there," said Planning and National Development Minister Wycliffe Oparanya. He said the government was dishing out free seeds and fertilisers to people displaced during two months of ethnic clashes after a disputed poll in December. Many of those driven out of their homes were farming communities in the agriculturally rich Rift Valley region. Inflation hit 18.2 percent in January and then 19.1 percent in February as supply routes to consumers were blocked by the fighting. "We need to make sure the internally displaced people are settled," Oparanya said. "I hope with increased production, we are likely to have prices of mainly food prices go down." The finance ministry would be tabling a supplementary budget in parliament which he said would provide money to subsidise fertilisers and seeds, he sa
